
[1]lure

   LURE, n.

   1. Something held out to call a hawk; hence,

   2. Any enticement; that which invites by the prospect of advantage or
   pleasure; as the lures of beauty or of gain.

                          LURE, v.i. To call hawks.

   Standing by one that lured loud and shrill.

   LURE, v.t. To entice; to attract; to invite by any thing that promises
                           pleasure or advantage.

   Lured on by the pleasure of the bait.

   And various science lures the learned eye.
